Indonesia Stock Movers: Aneka Tambang, Bank Mandiri, Elnusa

-- B y   B e r n i   M o e s t a f a
-- 
2011-12-01T09:15:43Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-12-01/indonesia-stock-movers-aneka-tambang-elnusa-medco-energi.html
Shares of the following companies had
 unusual (JCI)  moves in Indonesian trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of the close in Jakarta.  The Jakarta Composite Index rose for a fourth day, gaining
1.8 percent to 3,781.10, the steepest increase since Nov. 4.  Banks:  PT Bank Mandiri (BMRI)  , Indonesia’s largest
lender by assets, gained 3.9 percent to 6,650 rupiah.  PT Bank
Rakyat Indonesia (BBRI)  , the largest by revenue, rose 3.1
percent to 6,700 rupiah. Financial shares provided the biggest
boost to the composite index.  Indonesia’s inflation eased in November for a third month,
the central statistics office said today. Banking shares gained
as slower price gains supported the central bank’s decision to
cut its benchmark interest rate last month, according to Joseph
Pangaribuan, an analyst at PT Samuel Sekuritas Indonesia.  Energy companies:  PT Medco Energi Internasional (MEDC)  ,
Indonesia’s biggest listed oil company, increased 3.2 percent to
2,400 rupiah.  PT Energi Mega Persada (ENRG)  , the second-
largest, advanced 2 percent to 152 rupiah. Crude futures rose to
a two-week high, adding 0.6 percent to $100.36 a barrel in  New
York  yesterday. Oil last traded at $100.33 a barrel.  PT Aneka Tambang (ANTM)  , Indonesia’s second-largest
nickel producer, climbed 2.4 percent to 1,680 rupiah, the
biggest gain since Oct. 27. Aneka plans to increase the size of
a bond sale to 3 trillion rupiah ($329 million) from 1.5
trillion rupiah as investor demand reached 10 trillion rupiah,
Bisnis Indonesia reported, citing an unidentified executive.
Corporate Secretary Bimo Budi Satriyo didn’t answer three calls
to his office number.  PT Elnusa (ELSA)  , an Indonesian oil services company,
rose 2.4 percent to 210 rupiah, the biggest increase since Nov.
10. PT Benakat Petroleum Energy will spend 45 billion rupiah to
buy back 214.28 million of Elnusa’s shares at 210 rupiah each,
Bisnis Indonesia reported, citing Firlie Ganinduto, a director
at Benakat. Ganinduto and Elnusa Corporate Secretary Heru
Samodra couldn’t be reached when called at their offices.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Berni Moestafa in Jakarta at 
 bmoestafa@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
